Switching From Acceleration To Velocity Data

for(i in 3:ncol(data_x))
{
  for(j in 1:nrow(data_x))
  {
      data_x[j, i] = data_x[j, i-1] + data_x[j, i]
  }
}

for(i in 3:ncol(data_y))
{
  for(j in 1:nrow(data_y))
  {
    data_y[j, i] = data_y[j, i-1] + data_y[j, i]
  }
}

for(i in 3:ncol(data_z))
{
  for(j in 1:nrow(data_z))
  {
    data_z[j, i] = data_z[j, i-1] + data_z[j, i]
  }
}

The acceleration data is turned into velocity data by taking cumulative sums. For the rest of the project, velocity data is going to be used.

Creating Long Format

vec1 <- vector()
vec2 <- vector()

vec5 <- vector()
vec6 <- vector()

#time series id
k <- 1
for(i in 1:896)
{
  vec1[k:(k+314)] <- rep(data_x[i,1], 315)
  k <- k+315
}

#time index
vec2 = rep(1:315, 896)

#X
k <- 1
for(i in 1:nrow(data_x))
{
  for(j in 2:ncol(data_x))
  {
  vec3[k] <- data_x[i,j]
  k <- k+1
  }
}

#Y
k <- 1
for(i in 1:nrow(data_y))
{
  for(j in 2:ncol(data_y))
  {
    vec4[k] <- data_y[i,j]
    k <- k+1
  }
}

#Z
k <- 1
for(i in 1:nrow(data_z))
{
  for(j in 2:ncol(data_z))
  {
    vec5[k] <- data_z[i,j]
    k <- k+1
  }
}

#class
for(i in 1:length(vec1))
{
  if(vec1[i] == 1)
    vec6[i] = "a"
  else if(vec1[i] == 2)
    vec6[i] = "b"
  else if(vec1[i] == 3)
    vec6[i] = "c"
  else if(vec1[i] == 4)
    vec6[i] = "d"
  else if(vec1[i] == 5)
    vec6[i] = "e"
  else if(vec1[i] == 6)
    vec6[i] = "f"
  else if(vec1[i] == 7)
    vec6[i] = "g"
  else if(vec1[i] == 8)
    vec6[i] = "h"
}

PART A

x <- long_format$X[316:630]
y <- long_format$Y[316:630]
z <- long_format$Z[316:630]
sample_plot <- data.frame(x,y,z)
scatterplot3d(sample_plot[1:3], angle=300)

plot(sample_plot)

The time series id for this particular instance is 5 which corresponds to a gesture that starts from the bottom and simply goes upwards linearly. On the other hand, the 3D plot has a circular shape. However, it should be remembered that this result is given by the velocity data. An additional cummulative sum to compute the position data may result in a straight line.

When PCA is applied to reduce the data to 1 dimension from 3, it is noticed that in general, the randomly chosen couples from same class have similar plots. Therefore, it can be concluded that the dimensionality reduction was successful and the data still includes enough information to distinguish between classes.

When PCA is applied separately to each class, it is noticed that the 1st components usually cover about 50-60% of the total variance. The 1st components are different from each other in general. However, there also exist some classes that have pretty similar 1st components (such as classes 7 and 8), which points that the model was not able to distinguish between these two classes.
